ldo\nvitch, president of the Slavic Socletv\nof Moscow, arrived in Chicago today\nand announced that the United States\nis \"broke,\" temporarily ajt least, aa\nthe result of the recent financial\npanic. He- says he has found that'\nthe kings of finance of this country\nare unable to put their hands down\ninto their pockets and take out $225,-\n000,000 with which to carry out- a\nproposition which he declared had\nbeen made by an American syndicate\nto construct' a canal connecting tho\nBaltic with the Black Sea.\nThe Count refused to say what\nsyndicate made the offer, but said\nthat it was an Eastern concern back\ned by men who had controlled mil\nlions before the panic, but who are\nnow, he says, back numbers in the\nworld of finance 1\nFORGED NOTES:\ni .PLACED IN; BANK\nLOS ANGELES, April 20. White\nexamining the Bank of Calexico, in\nthe Imperial valley. State Bank Com\nmissioner W. S. Vawter of Santa\nMonica was amazed to find his name\nforged to. a note of $1000. The\ncommissioner came across a note foi\n$5000 In they name \"of W., S. Watson\nof this city, who was recently ar\nrested on a defalcation charge, a\nfact to which the commissioner called\nthe Lank officials' attention.,. He was\nInformed that the note was all right,\nbeing secured by two collateral notes\nfor $1000 each. Asking for them he\nsaw his own name and those of Vic\ntor Ponet and M. J. Nolan affixed\napparently all in the same handwrit\nlng. The other note bore the names\nof S. K. Llndlsy and T. R. Hunter,\nwritten In a .similar way. All are\nbelieved to be forgeries. -v\nRECEIVER SENDS\nINiHISiREPORT\n1\ni\nTO FIGHT REDUCTION;\nWINNIPEG, Man., April 20. A\nfederation of all the union men em\nployed in the shops of the Canadian\nPacific and the Canadian Northern\nrailroads was completed today., They\nwill fight the reductions in the new\nschedule to a finish, The companies\nclaim they are hot going (to pay all\nof the men. the same wages, but will\npay according to individual worth.\nThis Is the beginning, of a big fight\nbetween all of the unions and the\nrailways, both in Canada and the\nUnited States.\nHon. R. Douglass of ChurchilJ\ncounty, receiver of the property of\nMurray Scott, the discoverer of Won\nder, nled his report with the District\nCourt today.\nWhen the Scott interests became\ninvolved several months ago Doug'\nlass was placed in charge of the prop\nerty and money, the latter amounting;\nto $50,000 In cash, while the proper\nty was easily worth $150,000.\nSince that time claims and coun\nter claims have piled up against the\nproperty and money until there is\nnothing left for Scott\". Reno Gaz\nette. ''I J.,'.... .1 i in r\nLocation notices in triplicate-\nhandiest affair for prospectors and\nminers contains carbon 150 no\ntices in book. For sale at the Bon\nanza office.\nFive year1 old claret at $1.50 per\nBallon. IT. X Hail A 'Co. tf\nTry our four year md port nd\nsherry wines at $2.00 per gallon. H.\nJ. Hall Co. v,v tt\nC;0;F P EM\nI HANDBOOK\nN'if Edition issued, IMarcB, 1908.)\nSIZE Octavo.\nPAGES 1228.\nt CHAPTERS 23V 1\nSCOPE iThe copper industry of\nthe world. ;i -w h' t\nCOVERINGCopper History; Ge\nology, Geography, Chemistry, Min\neralogy, Mining, Milling, Leaching,\nSmelting, Refining, Brands, Grades,\nImpurities Alloys, Uses, Substitutes,\nTerminology, Deposits by Districts,\nStates,' Countries and Continents,\nMines In Detail, Statistics of Produc\ntion, Consumption, Imports, Exports,\nFinances,' Dividends, etc.\nThe Cbpper Handbook Is conceded-\nly the\nWORLD'S STANDARD REFERENCE BOOK\nON COPPER.\nTHE MINER needs the book for\nthe facts it gives him regarding Ge\nology, Mining, Copper Deposits and\nCopper Mines.\nTHE METALLURGIST needs the\noook ior tne racts it gives :hlm re\ngarding copper milling, leaching\nsmelting and refining.\nTHE COPPER CONSUMER needs\nthe book f6r every chapter it con\ntains. It tells what, and explains\nhow and why.\nTHE INVESTOR IN COPPER\nSHARES cannot afford to be without\nft. The Copper Ha